{"name":"Mathlib.NumberTheory.Bertrand","instances":[],"imports":["Init","Mathlib.Data.Nat.Choose.Factorization","Mathlib.Data.Nat.PrimeNormNum","Mathlib.NumberTheory.Primorial","Mathlib.Analysis.Convex.SpecificFunctions.Basic","Mathlib.Analysis.Convex.SpecificFunctions.Deriv"],"declarations":[{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.lean#L255-L255","name":"Nat.bertrand","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.html#Nat.bertrand","doc":"**Alias** of `Nat.exists_prime_lt_and_le_two_mul`."},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.lean#L236-L252","name":"Nat.exists_prime_lt_and_le_two_mul","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.html#Nat.exists_prime_lt_and_le_two_mul","doc":"**Bertrand's Postulate**: For any positive natural number, there is a prime which is greater than\nit, but no more than twice as large.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.lean#L225-L229","name":"Nat.exists_prime_lt_and_le_two_mul_succ","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.html#Nat.exists_prime_lt_and_le_two_mul_succ","doc":"Proves that Bertrand's postulate holds over all positive naturals less than n by identifying a\ndescending list of primes, each no more than twice the next, such that the list contains a witness\nfor each number ≤ n.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.lean#L206-L218","name":"Nat.exists_prime_lt_and_le_two_mul_eventually","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.html#Nat.exists_prime_lt_and_le_two_mul_eventually","doc":"Proves that Bertrand's postulate holds for all sufficiently large `n`.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.lean#L172-L199","name":"centralBinom_le_of_no_bertrand_prime","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.html#centralBinom_le_of_no_bertrand_prime","doc":"An upper bound on the central binomial coefficient used in the proof of Bertrand's postulate.\nThe bound splits the prime factors of `centralBinom n` into those\n1. At most `sqrt (2 * n)`, which contribute at most `2 * n` for each such prime.\n2. Between `sqrt (2 * n)` and `2 * n / 3`, which contribute at most `4^(2 * n / 3)` in total.\n3. Between `2 * n / 3` and `n`, which do not exist.\n4. Between `n` and `2 * n`, which would not exist in the case where Bertrand's postulate is false.\n5. Above `2 * n`, which do not exist.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.lean#L148-L161","name":"centralBinom_factorization_small","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.html#centralBinom_factorization_small","doc":"A lemma that tells us that, in the case where Bertrand's postulate does not hold, the prime\nfactorization of the central binomial coefficent only has factors at most `2 * n / 3 + 1`.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.lean#L128-L142","name":"bertrand_main_inequality","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.html#bertrand_main_inequality","doc":"The inequality which contradicts Bertrand's postulate, for large enough `n`.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.lean#L57-L115","name":"Bertrand.real_main_inequality","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/NumberTheory/Bertrand.html#Bertrand.real_main_inequality","doc":"A reified version of the `Bertrand.main_inequality` below.\nThis is not best possible: it actually holds for 464 ≤ x.\n"}]}